A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
First, Europe and the international community apply a cruelly ill-suited system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Second, in the face of the inefficacy of this system, populist actors continue to exploit fears in order to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction required some 70 years of relentless efforts.
It is why it is essential that this year a truly active approach be undertaken at both the European and global levels.
In September, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a robust global system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let us hope that states will be ready to engage in a concrete and lasting manner.
This necessary engagement was cruelly absent in 2015.
In fact, the international community could have limited the severity of last year's crisis if it had provided even minimal support to the frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which together host no fewer than four million refugees.
With only about 10 billion euros, these countries would have been better able to house, feed, and provide education for the refugees, thereby mitigating the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany alone up to 21 billion euros annually in the years to come.
But the financial implications of the crisis are disproportionate to its human and political cost.
More than one million people risked their lives last year crossing the Mediterranean, enduring a exhausting journey through the Balkans thereafter.
接近 4000 名移民因此丧生，许多欧洲国家则拒绝收留幸存者，转而背对他们。
The most cynical political actors have mercilessly exploited citizens' fears, promoting a hateful nationalist vision that either ignores or distorts the migrant experience.
In the United States, for example, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees resettled since September 11, 2001, has committed a terrorist act.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more in taxes than they receive in social benefits.
And yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with gaining political power in certain European countries, and are currently winning support even within formerly liberal strongholds.
The anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success leads traditional parties to promote an immigration-hostile policy as well.
This situation has significantly undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million of refugees arriving on its shores only managed to resettle 190.
Border controls have been reinstated, at least temporarily, in six Schengen-area countries.
To the rest of the world, the EU appears today nationalist and incompetent.
Of course, resolving this crisis concerns not only Europe; responsibility cannot be defined solely by geographical proximity.
Regardless, the EU likely faces today a threat to its very existence, which it can overcome only by demonstrating firmly its capacity for solidarity and international leadership.
It is therefore up to the member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The top priority must be to establish legal and secure pathways for refugees to reach Europe.
It is not about asserting that every vulnerable migrant must be welcomed.
It remains for the EU to be systematically more generous in determining the number of refugees to welcome, and to use orderly mechanisms to facilitate their entry.
Such a system would protect migrants while safeguarding Europe (through the ability to fully examine requests).
Beyond a deterrent approach aimed at discouraging asylum seekers from risking their lives crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would also project an image of solidarity towards frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
This equally important aspect would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to these efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a robust global system for protecting vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This goal will primarily require more countries to accept welcoming refugees.
In recent years, the UN Refugee Agency has managed to resettle only about 75,000 of the approximately 20 million annual refugees.
Many of them end up in a prolonged state of migration, with an average duration estimated at 25 years, trapped in a sort of purgatory and uncertain about the day they might return to their country.
In 2016, it is necessary for developed countries to agree to welcome annually a cumulative number close to one million refugees, either through their resettlement or by granting them a humanitarian, student, professional, or other visa.
Canada having pledged to welcome 50,000 Syrian refugees this year, this is a clearly achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community must support the integration of refugees in important hosting countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
In the current situation, these countries receive only a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually required per refugee for housing, food, healthcare, education, and vocational training during the first years of settlement.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of building or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, the water supply systems suffer from the pressure exerted by the massive arrival of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these hosting countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor market, and civic institutions.
But effective integration of migrants will be possible only if countries in Europe and elsewhere rid themselves of their prejudices regarding migrants.
If these are continued to be seen as a burden, or even a threat to security, reactionary political forces will keep gaining ground, depriving newcomers of opportunities and turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
However, if hosting states manage to integrate migrants with enthusiasm, everyone will benefit – including these countries (notably through income inflows).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved it could subordinate its national interests to a broader global objective: combating climate change.
In 2016, a similar effort is needed to build a better system for protecting migrants.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies worldwide.
